```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Breathing Layout Demo</title>
<style>
:root {
  --font-main: 'Crimson Text', Georgia, serif;
  --color-start: #333;
  --color-end: #111;
  --bg-start: #f4f3ef;
  --bg-end: #ffffff;
}

/* page container */
body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: var(--font-main);
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  background: var(--bg-start);
  color: var(--color-start);
  transition: background 1.5s ease, color 1s ease;
  padding: 8vh 10vw;
}

/* simulate gradual opening of space */
section {
  max-width: 40rem;
  margin: 6vh auto;
  transition: margin 1s ease, line-height 2s ease;
}

/* denser opening */
section.dense { line-height: 1.5; margin-top: 2vh; }
section.medium { line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 6vh; }
section.open { line-height: 2.1; margin-top: 10vh; }

/* calm end state */
footer {
  padding: 10vh 0;
  border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
  text-align: left;
  color: var(--color-end);
  background: var(--bg-end);
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<section class="dense">
  <p>Light. Breath. A horn. The floor moves.</p>
</section>

<section class="medium">
  <p>The street runs like a thought you can’t quite catch; everything gleams at the edges, too close, too bright — and somehow inviting. A hum that says <em>stay, stay</em>.</p>
</section>

<section class="open">
  <p>Then quiet. A hand against the wall, the pulse slowing, and the air remembers how to hold itself.</p>
</section>

<footer>
  <p>The hum remains, steady now, like breathing.</p>
</footer>

</body>
</html>
```

**How to use it**
- Drop it into a local HTML file and open in a browser; scroll slowly through each section.  
- Adjust line‑height or `margin-top` in `.dense`, `.medium`, `.open` until the timing matches your own breathing.  
- You can add a light fade‑in by animating body background from `--bg-start` to `--bg-end` as the user scrolls, but keep transitions slower than a second to preserve calm.  
- For Markdown‑based platforms, mimic these classes with heading levels or horizontal rules to suggest wider spacing between later sections.

This template isn’t flashy, but it embodies the design logic we’ve built: the visual field opens as the emotional temperature cools, letting the reading rhythm slow on its own.

