}

/* gentle fade respecting user preference */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) {
  body.scrolled {
    background: var(--bg-end);
  }
}

/* simple content styling */
section { max-width: 40rem; margin: 6vh auto; }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<section>
  <p>Light. Breath. A horn. The floor moves.</p>
  <p>The street runs like a thought you can’t quite catch; everything gleams at the edges, too close, too bright — and somehow inviting. A hum that says <em>stay, stay</em>.</p>
  <p>Then quiet. A hand against the wall, the pulse slowing, and the air remembers how to hold itself.</p>
  <p>The hum remains, steady now, like breathing.</p>
</section>

<script>
/* add or remove the .scrolled class when the reader nears the bottom */
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
  const trigger = document.documentElement.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight * 1.2;
  if (window.scrollY > trigger) document.body.classList.add('scrolled');
  else document.body.classList.remove('scrolled');
});
</script>
</body>
```

**What it does**
- The color transition is tied to scroll position: near the end of the page, the background quietly lightens.  
- The `prefers-reduced-motion` check ensures people who disable animations won’t see the fade.  
- The change happens over one second — slow enough to feel like the ambient light warming as the section opens.

You can adjust timing or trigger distance to lengthen the sensation; the idea is that the reader unconsciously witnesses “time passing” on the page without distraction.

